the 1905 Revolution, these intellectual elites increasingly put their faith in coercive programs of scientific social engineering.Their theories survived liberalism's political defeat in 1917 and meshed with the Bolsheviks' radical project for social transformation. They came to sanction the application of violent transformative measures against entire classes, culminating in the waves of state repression that accompanied forced industrialization and collectivization. Renovating Russia thus offers a powerful revisionist challenge to established views of the fate of liberalism in the Russian Revolution.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aLiberalismzRussiaxHistory. 0aMedical sciencesxHistoryxRussia. 0aMedical sciencesxHistoryxSoviet Union. 0aMedical scienceszRussiaxHistory. 0aMedical scienceszSoviet UnionxHistory. 0aSocial engineeringzRussiaxHistory. 0aSocial engineeringzSoviet UnionxHistory. 0aSocial sciencesxHistoryxRussia. 0aSocial sciencesxHistoryxSoviet Union. 0aSocial scienceszRussiaxHistory. 0aSocial scienceszSoviet UnionxHistory. 4aHistory. 4aSoviet & East European History. 7aHISTORY / Russia & the Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080146847640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801468476423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801468476/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles